First, we need to find the normal force. The normal force is equal in magnitude and opposite in direction to the force of gravity acting perpendicular to the incline. The force of gravity is $mg=(10\, \cancel{\text{kg}})(9.8\, \cancel{\text{m/s}^2}}) \approx 98 \, \cancel{\text{N}}$. So the normal force is $98\, \cancel{\text{N}} \cdot \text{m} \sin 30^\circ = 49 \, \cancel{\text{N}}$.

Next, we can calculate the frictional force opposing the block's motion up the incline. The maximum force of friction is $49 \, \cancel{\text{N}} \cdot \mu_k = 49 \, \cancel{\text{N}} \cdot 0.2 = 9.8 \, \cancel{\text{N}}$. Since the block is being pushed with a force of $100\, \cancel{\text{N}}$, we will use the maximum force of friction.

The net force acting on the block is the force of gravity acting down the incline, minus the force of friction acting up the incline: $$ma=mg \sin 30^\circ - f_k = (10\, \cancel{\text{kg}})(9.8\, \cancel{\text{m/s}^2}}) \sin 30^\circ - 9.8\, \cancel{\text{N}} = 49 \, \cancel{\text{N}} - 9.8\, \cancel{\text{N}} = 39.2\, \cancel{\text{N}}.$$Solving for $a$, we find  \begin{align*}
a &= \dfrac{49\, \cancel{\text{N}} - 9.8\, \cancel{\text{N}}}{10\, \cancel{\text{kg}}}}{\text{m/s}^2} \approx \boxed{3.92 \, \text{m/s}^2}.
\end{align*}

